  "timeboxMinutes": 15,
  "prompt": "A teammate wrote `fetch_all_bookings`, and it only returns the first page. Your job is to debug it.\n\nThe public function signature stays `fetch_all_bookings(base_url)`. Return every booking dict from every page, exactly like the first pagination problem.\n\nThe API contract is:\n\n```python\n{\"data\": [booking_dict, ...], \"next_cursor\": \"...\" | None}\n```\n\nReturn contract:\n\n- Return `list[dict]`.\n- Preserve API order.\n- Return booking dicts unchanged.\n- Return `[]` if the API is empty.\n\nWhat to look for:\n\n- Page-one-only bugs usually mean the code reads the wrong cursor field.\n- The response key is `next_cursor`, not `cursor`.\n- Pass the cursor back in the next request's `params`.\n\nShared fake API note: this uses the in-process `requests` mock described in the Ramp Travel module guide; there is no real network.\n\nValidation focus: fixing the cursor field, fetching multiple pages, no duplicate first page, and preserving order.",
  "signature": {
    "name": "fetchAllBookings",
    "inputs": [
      {
        "name": "base_url",
        "type": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      }
    ],
    "output": {
      "type": "array",
      "items": {
        "type": "any"
      }
    }
  },
